\onecolumn
\section{Supplementary material}

\section*{Supplementary Methods: DNA Methylation Microarray}

\subsection*{S1. Quality Control of Methylation Microarray Data}

Raw Illumina HumanMethylation450K IDAT files (GSE134379) were imported and processed using the \texttt{minfi} framework. Initial quality control was performed using detection \textit{P}-values to identify low-quality probes and samples. Samples with more than 5\% failed probes and probes failing in more than 5\% of samples were excluded from further analysis.

Quality metrics, including signal intensity distributions and sample-wise detection rates, were assessed using Minfi-generated QC reports. Density plots of beta values after ENmix quantile normalization in both cerebellum and MTG displayed the expected bimodal distribution with strong overlap across samples, indicating effective normalization and overall high data quality, with no evidence of major technical artifacts (Figure ~\ref{beta_MTG},~\ref{beta_CB}). 
Principal component analysis of beta values  (Figure~\ref{PCA_MTG},~\ref{PCA_CB}) was used to evaluate global data structure and identify potential batch effects or outlier samples. No strong batch-driven clustering or extreme outliers were observed, indicating overall good data quality.
The distribution of delta beta values for both MTG and CB is centered near zero, indicating that the majority of CpG sites show small methylation differences between Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and non-demented (ND) samples, with a subset exhibiting larger positive or negative delta-beta values (Figure ~\ref{fig:hist_delta_beta_CBL}, ~\ref{fig:hist_delta_beta_MTG}). 

\subsection*{S2. Software and R Packages Used}

All methylation analyses were performed in R using Bioconductor packages. Data import, quality control, probe annotation, and object handling were carried out using \texttt{minfi}. Background correction, dye-bias correction, and normalization were implemented using the ENmix framework. Differential methylation analysis was performed using \texttt{limma}, and differentially methylated regions were identified using \texttt{DMRcate}.

Additional packages were used for data manipulation, visualization, and annotation, including \texttt{IlluminaHuman
Methylation450kanno.ilmn12.hg19}, \texttt{AnnotationDbi}, \texttt{org.Hs.eg.db}, \texttt{ggplot2}, and \texttt{dplyr}.


\subsection*{S3. Preprocessing, Normalization, and Downstream Analysis}

Due to the large dataset size (808 samples), preprocessing was performed in nine batches (eight batches of 100 samples and one batch of eight samples) to accommodate computational constraints. Each batch was processed independently using identical preprocessing pipelines.

Background correction and dye-bias normalization were applied using the ENmix framework. Probes overlapping known single-nucleotide polymorphisms, probes mapping to multiple genomic locations, rs-probes, and probes located on sex chromosomes were removed following established guidelines \cite{zhou2016}. Filtered probes were mapped to the genome using \texttt{mapToGenome()} and stored as \texttt{MethylSet} objects \cite{aryee2014}.

After batch-level preprocessing, datasets were merged by intersecting the set of high-confidence probes shared across all batches. The merged dataset was subsequently split by tissue (middle temporal gyrus and cerebellum), and ENmix quantile normalization was applied separately to each tissue \cite{xu2016}. Beta values were calculated to represent methylation proportions, and M-values were derived using log$_2$ transformation of methylated and unmethylated intensities for use in differential methylation analysis.

Differentially methylated regions were identified using \texttt{DMRcate} with smoothing and effect-size filtering based on $\lvert\Delta\beta\rvert$ thresholds. Final region-level results included genomic coordinates, number of CpGs per region, and direction of methylation change.




\section*{Supplementary Methods: RNAseq}
\subsection*{S4. RNA-seq Quality Control}

Raw RNA-seq count data derived from post-mortem human hippocampal tissue were assessed for overall quality and sample structure prior to differential expression analysis. Genes with very low expression were filtered out to reduce noise in dispersion estimation; specifically, genes with a total count of ten or fewer across all samples were excluded.

Regularized log (rlog) transformation was applied to generate variance-stabilized expression values for exploratory analysis. Principal component analysis (PCA) was performed to assess global transcriptional structure and sample clustering (Figure ~\ref{pca_rna}. The first two principal components explained a substantial fraction of the variance, revealing partial separation between Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and control samples, alongside considerable within-group variability.

Library sizes were inspected to assess sequencing depth and variability across samples. Read counts ranged from approximately 11 to 35 million reads per sample, with moderate variability between samples and no extreme outliers warranting exclusion. Size-factor normalization implemented by DESeq2 was used to account for differences in sequencing depth.

\subsection*{S5. Software and R Packages Used}

RNA-seq analyses were performed in R using Bioconductor packages. Differential expression analysis and normalization were carried out using \texttt{DESeq2}. Log$_2$ fold-change shrinkage was performed using the \texttt{apeglm} method as implemented in DESeq2. Gene annotation was performed using \texttt{org.Hs.eg.db}.

Additional packages used for data manipulation and visualization included \texttt{dplyr}, \texttt{ggplot2}, and \texttt{tidyr}.

\subsection*{S6. RNA-seq Preprocessing and Differential Expression Analysis}

Raw RNA-seq count data (GSE184942) were imported into R, and sample metadata was aligned to the count matrix using GSM accession identifiers. Differential expression analysis was performed using DESeq2 \cite{love2014}. A \texttt{DESeqDataSet} object was constructed with the design formula
$\text{Counts} \sim \text{tissue}$,
where \texttt{tissue} encoded Alzheimer’s disease versus healthy control status.


Raw RNA-seq count data were filtered to remove lowly expressed genes prior to differential expression analysis, reducing noise in dispersion estimation. Library size normalization was performed internally by DESeq2 through size-factor estimation.

For quality assessment and exploratory analysis, variance-stabilized expression values were generated using regularized log (rlog) transformation. Principal component analysis (PCA) was performed to evaluate global expression patterns and sample structure. PCA revealed moderate separation between AD and control samples, with substantial within-group variability, consistent with the heterogeneous nature of post-mortem hippocampal tissue. No extreme outliers were detected.

Differential expression results were visualized using MA and volcano plots. Gene identifiers were annotated using the \texttt{org.Hs.eg.db} database to map Entrez Gene identifiers to gene symbols and gene names.



\section*{Supplementary Material}

\subsection*{S7. Computational Environment}

All analyses were performed using R (version 4.5.2) within RStudio (version 2025.9.2.418). 
Computations were executed on a high-performance computing (HPC) cluster using an 
Anaconda-managed R environment. Job scheduling and resource management were handled 
using the SLURM workload manager. 

All scripts used for data preprocessing, statistical analysis, and visualization are 
provided in the Supplementary Material to ensure reproducibility of the results.

\subsection*{ S8. Supplementary Note: Generative AI}

AI-based language assistance tools (ChatGPT version 5.2) were used to support editing to appropriate script format (for example: HPC SLURM/PBS). All analyses, results, and interpretations were performed and verified 
by the author.

